    <h2 class="w-h2 reveal" data-stagger="2">Weather first.<br />More verticals on the&nbsp;way.</h2>
    <p class="w-lead reveal" data-stagger="3">The hard part isn't weather. It's building a data layer that treats every source with the same settlement discipline — source priority, temporal honesty, agent-safe schemas. Once that holds, extending it is an ingest problem, not a design problem. One Python SDK, growing one vertical at a&nbsp;time.</p>

    <div class="w-pillar-grid">
      <div class="w-pillar reveal">
        <h3>Sports</h3>
        <p>Game results, scores, and injury reports from official league feeds. NFL, NBA, MLB, NHL, soccer. Every resolution attached to its source of truth, so your agent never bets on a settlement it can't&nbsp;verify.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="w-pillar reveal" data-stagger="2">
        <h3>Economics</h3>
        <p>FOMC decisions, jobs reports, CPI, GDP. Publication-time semantics so your backtest sees what the market saw at decision time. BLS, BEA, Fed — parsed, normalized, and paired to the contracts they&nbsp;settle.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="w-pillar reveal">
        <h3>Elections &amp; politics</h3>
        <p>Official state-board returns, timeline-aware so running a model on election night doesn't leak tomorrow's data into yesterday's decision. Every settlement verifiable against the primary&nbsp;source.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="w-pillar reveal" data-stagger="2">
        <h3>Climate &amp; catastrophes</h3>
        <p>Annual temperature records, hurricane paths, seasonal snowfall. Long-horizon settlement data for longer-duration markets. Same source discipline as hourly weather, at a different&nbsp;cadence.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
